1.) Why bytecode? Why does Java compile to platform-neutral bytecode instead of a native .exe on each OS? (Exercise 2 WORA)
    A: Platform independence, write once, run anywhere

2.) Class name vs file path. Why does java HelloWorld omit .class, and what goes wrong if you type java HelloWorld.java or java helloworld? (Exercises 1–2)
    A: 'java' is taking in a class name param. Not a file name. This is handled internally. javac creates the class file beforehand. ... ClassnotFound exception occurs

3.) Stack frames. What is created when main calls Calculator.add, and what happens to that frame on return? (Exercise 6 → Lab Steps 5–6)
    A: The JVM pushes a new stack frame containing 'add''s parameters, local vars, and operand stack, and return address. On return , frame is popped off the stack. Stack memory is reclaimed immediately on pop, no gc needed unlike heap objects

4.) Heap identity. In Employee emp = new Employee(101, "Aman"), what lives on the stack versus the heap? (Exercise 7 → Lab Step 7)
    A: Reference to var location for 'emp' on stack. On heap: Employee Object (created by new) with fields. Also String object

5.) Class loading cost. Why does java -verbose:class Employee print dozens of JDK classes before your Employee line? (Exercise 4 → Lab Step 8)
    A: The JDK is loaded first in Bootstrap class loader. Before it can execute anything. Then Employee Object/classes are loaded by lazy loading.

6.) -Xmx / source of truth. What does -Xmx constrain, and if .java and .class disagree after an edit without javac, which file does java execute? (Lab-only depth + Exercise 2)
    A: Maximum heap size. It will execute the .class file (last compiled version) if running class name (java Hello) , but will re-compile and run .java when included (java Hello.java).

7.) Forward look. How will Maven (mvn compile) change tooling but not the javac → bytecode → JVM story for the future CRM?
    A: Maven will include javac under the hood. Not change the compile pipeline. Along with dependency management





